uyjs6sls_VUIFx3BrjzrnDtSJr_rbt6FhQf5zDrL1KpVllD2M2NhskRja0Nyu-AQnXELfaoM9D8W1cLc2sheQlYKgiSTbWYYib7R1mdv5mH57SqCaLWx_VDz-j5vX_9qGEq6SiotJvBRQWg=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Native Image Building**\\n\\nI’m reflecting on whether `Class.forName` in `sun.misc` can be resolved from the application classpath. It seems that Native Image could block this due to the package being in a named module. I’m wondering if I could patch it in a native image build by using `buildArgs(\\\"-J--patch-module=jdk.unsupported=...\\\")`. But wait, does `-J` pass to the JVM running the builder, instead of the analysis classpath? Hmm, I'm not so sure.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Java classloading**\\n\\nI'm considering running a small Java test, which might be okay but not absolutely necessary. I wonder if I could add a test in the same JVM using a custom class loader. When using Class.forName without a loader parameter, it pulls from the caller's defining class loader. Can I load the Ant jar with a custom class loader that prioritizes child classes, including a generated sun.misc.BASE64Encoder? \\n\\nI’m contemplating whether loading from a custom class loader could let me access sun.misc, even with the modules involved. But since java.* is restricted, will this lead to a SecurityException? I need to think carefully about defining classes in sun.misc and whether URLClassLoader is viable here. I’ll need to check for potential sealing issues to ensure this works as expected.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering public API requirements**\\n\\nI need to ensure that my test uses the public API. I won't be using the compile-time Get, since I'm thinking of loading Ant classes dynamically instead. There's an often-cited rule about avoiding direct reflection unless the public API calls for it, which makes me feel uncertain. I'm questioning whether this dynamic classloading approach is suitable since it might not be standard. I also need to confirm that I can access org.apache.tools.ant.taskdefs.Get from the library. \\n\\nWith a custom URLClassLoader, can the call sites still reference the same class? I wonder if JaCoCo would handle this correctly. I just realized that a native image won't support dynamic loading of a jar after the build; however, if the classpath is known prior to the build, what could that mean for my setup?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_aTUDIlpJLisxOf2smyX53OI7|fc_04424b36390761bc0169fc8769a5cc8190b6a672d41b099fbf", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "tasks.withType(Test).configureEach {\n    dependsOn generateLegacyBase64Encoder\n    jvmArgs '--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED'\n    doFirst {\n        jvmArgs \"-Xbootclasspath/a:${generatedLegacyClassesDir.get().asFile.absolutePath}\"\n    }\n}\n", "newText": "tasks.withType(Test).configureEach {\n    dependsOn generateLegacyBase64Encoder\n    jvmArgs '--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED'\n    doFirst {\n        jvmArgs '--add-modules=jdk.unsupported',\n                \"--patch-module=jdk.unsupported=${generatedLegacyClassesDir.get().asFile.absolutePath}\"\n    }\n}\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 495, "output": 1755, "cacheRead": 59904, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 62154, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778157393074, "responseId": "resp_04424b36390761bc0169fc875214108190a60882da78c005cb"}}
